as declined more than 20 percent since 2017—Moore takes us with him as he performs whale necropsies on animals stranded on beaches, in his independent research alongside whalers using explosive harpoons, and as he tracks injured whales to deliver sedatives. The whales’ plight is a complex, confounding, and disturbing one. We learn of existing but poorly enforced conservation laws and of perennial (and often failed) efforts to balance the push for fisheries profit versus the protection of endangered species caught by accident. But despite these challenges, Moore’s tale is an optimistic one. He shows us how technologies for ropeless fishing and the acoustic tracking of whale migrations make a dramatic difference. And he looks ahead with hope as our growing understanding of these extraordinary creatures fuels an ever-stronger drive for change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aBowhead whalexEffect of human beings on. 0aNorthern right whalexEffect of human beings on. 0aNorthern right whale-Effect of human beings on. 0aRight whalesxResearch. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh  aendangered, species, humpback, pilot, fin, North, Atlantic, ocean, fishing, commecial, shipping, seafood, overfishing, sea, environment, global, warming, climate, change, marine, conservation, mammals, biology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107391900 cprintz978022680304340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226803180423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226803180/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles